properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Rain or wet snow for the Islands Thursday night, followed by colder temperatures, flurries and strong winds for Friday and Saturday. A weather system will bring rain to the Islands beginning late in the day Thursday, then change to wet snow overnight. Flurries will develop on Friday as colder air and stronger winds move into the region from the northwest. Saturday will be an unseasonably cold and blustery day with frequent flurries that could give a few centimetres of accumulation. The storm could cause higher than normal water levels during high tide as well as large waves and rough and pounding surf, mainly along coastlines where winds blow onshore Friday night and Saturday. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NSstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NSStorm.

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Significant snowfall and poor driving conditions expected. Total snowfall: up to 15 cm except locally 15 to 30 cm over higher terrain. Locations: Corner Brook and vicinity, Gros Morne, Deer Lake - Humber Valley, and Green Bay - White Bay. Time span: Friday morning through Friday evening. Remarks: Snowfall accumulations are likely to vary considerably with the highest amounts expected through inland and higher elevations of Green Bay - White Bay and higher elevations between Deer Lake and Corner Brook and Deer Lake and Gros Morne. The snow will taper off Friday night but flurries, snow squalls, and strong westerly winds will develop again early Saturday along the west coast and persist through the day. ### Rapidly accumulating snow could make travel difficult over some locations. Snowfall warnings are issued when significant snowfall is expected. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Wintry weather expected for parts of Nova Scotia Friday night into Saturday. A low pressure system is expected to bring some rain to the province tonight and Friday. Colder air will move in behind this system later on Friday and persist on Saturday. As this colder air arrives from the northwest, showers will turn to periods of snow late Friday afternoon or Friday evening which could give local accumulations and potentially hazardous driving conditions, especially to the Annapolis Valley, northern Nova Scotia and parts of Cape Breton Island. Saturday will be a cold and blustery day across the entire province with onshore flurries and temperatures struggling to climb above zero in some areas. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Rain and snow followed by colder temperatures expected over New Brunswick. A low pressure system is expected to bring rain to southern New Brunswick beginning this afternoon with snow expected over northern regions. The rain/snow boundary will likely be across central New Brunswick. Rainfall amounts of 15 to 30 millimetres are possible over southern sections with 5 to 10 centimetres of snow possible for the northern and central areas of the province by Friday morning. Saturday will be mainly sunny but remain cold across the province as temperatures will struggle to reach the freezing mark in many areas. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada.
